events.originalText: In the "Minneapolis Miracle", American football player Stefon Diggs caught a 61-yard touchdown pass that secured the Minnesota Vikings' victory in the National Football Conference divisional playoff game.
events.subtitle: Minneapolis Miracle
events.headline: Stefon Diggs' 61-yard touchdown secures Minnesota Vikings' victory in NFC divisional playoff game

events.originalText: Tunisian president Zine el Abidine Ben Ali fled the country after several violent protests.
events.subtitle: Zine El Abidine Ben Ali
events.headline: Tunisian president Zine el Abidine Ben Ali flees country amid violent protests

events.originalText: Austrian logician Kurt Gödel, who suffered from an obsessive fear of being poisoned, died of starvation after his wife was hospitalized and unable to cook for him.
events.subtitle: Logic
events.headline: Austrian logician Kurt Gödel dies of starvation due to fear of being poisoned

events.originalText: Elvis Presley's (pictured)  concert Aloha from Hawaii via Satellite was broadcast live to audiences in Asia and Oceania.
events.subtitle: Elvis Presley
events.headline: Elvis Presley's concert broadcast live to Asia and Oceania

events.originalText: The self-proclaimed Republic of Biafra in southeastern Nigeria surrendered to the federal government less than three years after declaring independence, ending the Nigerian Civil War.
events.subtitle: Biafra
events.headline: Republic of Biafra surrenders to Nigerian government, ending Civil War

events.originalText: A major fire and series of explosions aboard the U.S. Navy aircraft carrier USS Enterprise killed 28 sailors, injured 314 others, and destroyed 15 aircraft.
events.subtitle: USS Enterprise fire
events.headline: Major fire and explosions aboard USS Enterprise kill 28 sailors

events.originalText: The Human Be-In, a countercultural event forming a prelude to the Summer of Love, was held in San Francisco's Golden Gate Park.
events.subtitle: Human Be-In
events.headline: Human Be-In event held in San Francisco's Golden Gate Park

events.originalText: The Reserve Bank of Australia, the country's central bank and banknote-issuing authority, was established.
events.subtitle: Reserve Bank of Australia
events.headline: Reserve Bank of Australia established as central bank and banknote-issuing authority

events.originalText: Hindu spiritual leader Kripalu Maharaj was named the fifth original jagadguru, meaning 'world teacher'.
events.subtitle: Kripalu Maharaj
events.headline: Hindu spiritual leader Kripalu Maharaj named fifth original jagadguru

events.originalText: Josip Broz Tito was inaugurated as the first president of Yugoslavia.
events.subtitle: Josip Broz Tito
events.headline: Josip Broz Tito inaugurated as first president of Yugoslavia

events.originalText: Winston Churchill, Franklin D. Roosevelt, Charles de Gaulle, and Henri Giraud met in Casablanca to plan the Allies' European strategy for the next phase of World War II.
events.subtitle: Winston Churchill
events.headline: Churchill, Roosevelt, de Gaulle, and Giraud meet in Casablanca to plan Allies' European strategy

events.originalText: Norway claimed Queen Maud Land, a 2.7-million km2 (1.0-million sq mi) region of Antarctica, as a dependent territory.
events.subtitle: Queen Maud Land
events.headline: Norway claims Queen Maud Land in Antarctica as dependent territory

events.originalText: The England cricket team employed bodyline tactics against Australia during a Test match at the Adelaide Oval, the peak of a major controversy in the sport.
events.subtitle: England cricket team
events.headline: England cricket team employs bodyline tactics against Australia in Test match

events.originalText: An earthquake registering 6.2 Mw struck Kingston, Jamaica, resulting in approximately 1,000 deaths.
events.subtitle: 1907 Kingston earthquake
events.headline: Earthquake in Kingston, Jamaica results in approximately 1,000 deaths

events.originalText: Giacomo Puccini's opera Tosca, based on the play La Tosca by French dramatist Victorien Sardou, premiered at the Teatro Costanzi in Rome.
events.subtitle: Giacomo Puccini
events.headline: Puccini's opera Tosca premieres at Teatro Costanzi in Rome

events.originalText: Sweden and Denmark–Norway signed the Treaty of Kiel, whereby Frederick VI of Denmark ceded Norway to Sweden in return for the Swedish holdings in Pomerania.
events.subtitle: Denmark–Norway
events.headline: Sweden and Denmark–Norway sign Treaty of Kiel, ceding Norway to Sweden

events.originalText: Philip V (pictured), the first Bourbon king of Spain, abdicated in favour of his seventeen-year-old eldest son, who became Louis I.
events.subtitle: Philip V of Spain
events.headline: Philip V abdicates in favor of son Louis I, becoming first Bourbon king of Spain

events.originalText: King Andrew III died without any male heirs, ending the Árpád dynasty, which had ruled Hungary since the late 9th century.
events.subtitle: Andrew III of Hungary
events.headline: King Andrew III dies, ending Árpád dynasty in Hungary
